Germany is the first in Europe to allow "uncertain gender" when registering children
Germany will be the first country in Europe, where "uncertain" will be allowed in the registration of children born with unclear gender, instead of male or female.
The parents of the child will be allowed to leave the gender "uncertain" in the birth certificate registry.
Instead of "f" (female gender) or "m" (male gender), parents can initially record "x" (uncertain gender).
This decision is aimed to not push parents to hurry with gender clarification surgery.
According to the statistics, one in 2,000 babies in the world is born with unclear gender.
Anger over the verdict of one organizer of the Bali terrorist attack
The remaining survivors and relatives of 202 victims of the 2002 Bali bombing reacted angrily to the verdict of Umar Patek, the last of the conspirators to appear in court, and stated that he should be shot.
Patek, who spent nearly 10 years on the run as one of the most wanted men in south-east Asia, was yesterday sentenced to 20 years in prison for his role in building the explosive devices used in the attack.
He could be freed within 15 years, if he gets parole.
The 45th defendant was found guilty of mass murder as a result of attacks on two night club in the popular tourist area of kuta, during which killed 202 people, including 88 Australians, and injured dozens more.
He was also found guilty on a number of other charges related to terrorism, including in a wave of bombings of churches across Indonesia on Christmas Eve in 2000.
Prosecutors have suggested life imprisonment, although they could request that the man, nicknamed "the master bomb-maker" for his reputation for making explosives, should be sentenced to death.
This decision evokes painful memories for June Kortin, a mother from Perth who lost her 39-year-old daughters Jane and Jenny in the terrorist attack, almost ten years ago.
Barely concealing her own tears, she said that Patek was supposed to be sentenced to death.
"I really believe that he should follow in the footsteps of the other guys.
He must appear before the firing squad, "the AAP quoted Ms. Kortin.
"I have to live every day knowing that I will never have grandchildren and I will never see my daughters."
The "Sari" club was destroyed when a massive explosive device, left in a van parked outside, detonated just after 11 p.m. on October 12, 2002.
