After that attack, he fell into a month-long coma and "died" three times, while connected to a life-support system.
Mr Hughes said that Patek should share the fate of three other members of the terrorist cell of "Jemaah Islamiyah", responsible for the bloodbath, along with Amrozi, Mukhlasa and Imam Samudry who were executed four years ago.
Indeed, this guy deserves the death penalty all the more.
To save his life, well, there is no reason to save his life.
To get 20 years after killing 202 people and wounding hundreds is not so much.
Patek is the last of the terrorist attack in Bali, to appear before a court of law.
He was hiding for almost a decade, but in the end was arrested in January 2011 in the Pakistani town of Abbottabad, where U.S. forces killed former al-Qaeda boss Osama bin Laden less than four months later.
During the trial, an FBI agent testified that the intelligence indicated that Patek was in Pakistan to meet bin Laden in an attempt to restore the ties between southeast Asian terrorist groups and al-Qaeda.
"He didn't give up," said Ms. Kortin.
Until recently he regretted nothing about how much grief he caused others.
The judgement came in the run-up to the 10th anniversary of the terrorist attack, which will be celebrated later this year in Bali and Australia.
"This year there will be a lot of tears," said Ms. Kortin.
Patek can still appeal his sentence.
