Scientists shed light on how a dog's tail is related to its mood.
Earlier research has shown that happy dogs hold their tail on the right side (from the point of view of a dog), while alarmed dogs hold their tail mainly on the left side.
But now, scientists say that other members of the dog's family may notice these subtle differences in tail position and react to them.
Professor Giorgio Vallortigara, a Professor at Trent University, says: "it is well known that in people the left and right side of the brain are involved differently in shaping the stimulators of positive or negative emotions."
Here we have tried to look at this and many other species.
He added that just like humans, in dogs the right side of the brain controls the left side of the body, and vice versa, and the two hemispheres play different roles in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to various tails positions of other dogs, the researchers watched the animals when they watched films about other dogs.
They measured the frequency of the animals' heartbeat and analyzed their behavior.
Perhaps soon we will understand why their tails sometimes heading in one direction, and sometimes — in another
Professor Vallortigara said: "We showed videos of dogs with dogs — either a natural version or a silhouette, to get rid of any of the other distorting factors, and we could manipulate the tail movement and direct more tail left or right."
When the animals have seen that nothing in the rest of the tail expressing the dog moved to the right (from the point of view of the observed dog's tail), they were totally relaxed.
But when they noticed that the tail was left mainly (again from the point of view of observed dog's tail), their heartbeat increased and they looked alarmed.
Professor Vallortigara said that he does not think that dogs deliberately communicated with each other using these movements.
In fact, he believes that the dogs have learned from their experience, about what movements they should worry about, and what not to.
He says: "If there are several meetings with other dogs and holding their tail to one side is often associated with more friendly behavior, while the other side is less friendly behavior, then the dog reacts on the basis of that experience."
The researchers say that these results may give owners and veterinarians a deeper understanding of emotions of the animal.
An expert in the field of behavior of dogs, John Bradshaw, a visiting researcher in the Veterinary School at Bristol University, said it was not the first study to test whether a value for dogs left and right side.
Last year a group of scientists from the University of Lincoln found that dogs turn the head to the left when they look at an aggressive dog, and to the right when they look at peaceful dog.
And in other scientific work at the University of Victoria in Canada, he reported: "Dogs often approached the Sobak robot when its tail was held to the left, not right, rather than become alarmed — the opposite of behavior towards the Italian study."
He said that the differences could be due to the fact that dogs in various studies are not entirely susceptible to animals in films or Sobak robots as dogs.
It could be useful to study how dogs react to these dogs, he explained.
"While on various mammals there is enough evidence that the two hemispheres of the brain are used for various purposes, many details are yet to be specified, and dogs are no exception," he said.
However, given the ease with which their behavior can be observed, perhaps, soon we will understand why their tails sometimes heading in one direction, and sometimes — in another.
