A trip on the dirt, the rivers and the jungle to provide free medical care
Dr. Georges Belle provides free medical care in rural areas in Cameroon
Belle and his team spend nearly every weekend, taking hundreds of patients
In this African country there are not so many doctors — just one in 5,000 people
Cast your vote here, or through your mobile device
Dr. Georges Belle — one of the top 10 CNN heroes of 2013.
You can vote for him or for any of the other top 10 CNN heroes, so he becomes a hero of the year.
This man receives $250,000 to continue his remarkable work.
For 21 years, Georges Belle saw his father come back to life and again sink into unconsciousness, wandering across hospitals, which were not properly equipped to help him.
Dzhamef Belle was injured in a car crash in 1981 near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon.
At first he had only a broken hand but the contagion spread to the brain and caused an infection, which affected him to the end of his life.
"Cameroon had no neurosurgeons," said Georges Belle.
If we had the money, we would have flown him out from Cameroon.
Instead, Belle years accompanied his father in overcrowded clinics and hospitals receiving any treatment that they could get.
"It is not easy," said Belle.
— You can leave from your house at 5 a.m. to run back to the hospital to be first, but you are not the first.
So many patients.
Some may die because they have to wait.
The situation is not much changed since Belle's father died in 2002.
According to the World Health Organization, in cameroon there is only one doctor per 5,000 people.
By comparison, the ratio in the United States — one doctor per 413 people.
And even if Cameroonians could go to a doctor, many of them could not afford it.
Two out of five people in this country live below the poverty line, and nearly three quarters of health expenditures in it are private.
"Their only problem is poverty," said Belle.
— And because of poverty they cannot enjoy their lives. "
Seeing the suffering of his father and so many of his compatriots, Belle became determined to do something with this.
Last year, Dr Georges Belle and his team of volunteers performed 700 free operations.
He became a doctor and vascular surgeon at the central hospital in Yaoundé.
He also founded the non-profit organization ASCOVIME, which organizes trips to the countryside on weekends to provide free medical care.
Since 2008, he and his band of volunteers helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and another 30 people drive in vans with medical supplies chained to their roofs and travel over rough terrain to visit villages in need of help.
They do not always have luck.
More than once they had to push vehicles through rivers and mud.
But when they arrive, they are welcomed as the true heroes: their arrival becomes a holiday with songs and dances and the best rooms local residents can provide.
Free medical care in these villages really is a cause for celebration, and Belle with his broad smile and infinite energy is more than happy to join in the fun.
The next morning the team starts to take hundreds of patients.
"We have 500 people on each trip," said Belle.
They come from the whole vicinity within a radius of 60 kilometers from the village, and they come on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics provides a variety of medical services.
Many people get treatment for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, disease, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may receive donated crutches points or free birth certificates - documents needed for schools that many poor families simply cannot afford.
In the evening, the brigade performs simple operations under local anesthesia.
Surgery is usually held in a school or municipal building, or in a house; after the procedure, patients come and go in the operation area to make space for the next person.
Using a generator to provide lighting operating and sanitization equipment Belle and its volunteers work until the early hours of Sunday.
This determination sets a frantic pace, but teams of rural musicians usually help.
"They all night beat the drums, so we were awake and continued to work," said Belle.
On Sunday, the brigade members are sent back to town, tired, but proud of their work.
This group, consisting of Cameroonians, foreign doctors and medical students, performed 700 free operations last year, and they know that their aid could be of great value for those they help.
One man explained that he obtained free surgery for the hernia treatment will allow him to work again.
"This will change the future for me and my family," the man said.
In addition to these weekend clinics and his work as a hospital surgeon Belle also works nights in a private medical clinics around Yaoundé.
It is this second work, he said, that provides 60% of the funding for his a nonprofit organization; the rest is covered by private donations.
"I don't even know when he sleeps," said Cathy O'Mally, a second year medical student from Dreksel University in Philadelphia, a volunteer in Belle's group.
He is always either in the hospital or trying to earn money for the organization to continue with these campaigns.
For future doctors and nurses, such as about O'Malley who come from the United States and Europe to join Belle in implementing his objectives, it is an opportunity to practice which they would never have got at home.
"We have got to assist on operations, where we helped remove the blood stains or keep the tools for doctors Belle", — said about O'Malley.
Being a nursing student, you would never get this kind of opportunity in America.
Student volunteers usually pay for their own travel to Cameroon, often arriving with medicines.
But on arrival in Yaounde Bell pays for their meals, transport and education.
"He is a hero, without a doubt," said about O'Malley.
He gives his life to this organisation, and his desire to help the people of Cameroon is infinite.
For Belle the almost constant work load is not an ordeal.
Helping others to live a happy life, to fulfil this promise to his father — that is what brings him great joy.
"I am so happy when i do this job," said Belle.
— And I think about my father.
I hope he sees what I do.
I do it to make people laugh, to reduce their pain.
Go to the ASCOVIME site and see how you can help.
