Speech Gene Stimulated Synapse Formation
Scientists from Johns Hopkins University and Mount Sinai Hospital-New York Medical School found the protein that allows the Foxp2 "speech gene" to carry out its function by stimulating the formation of new connections between neurons.
The study is published in the journal Science, you can read his summary on their website.
The Foxp2 gene is the first known gene whose function is directly associated with speech.
It's role was established in 2001, thanks to the discovery of a family of several people who could not utter words correctly and sometimes could not even understand each other.
Researchers found that family members have a disrupted Foxp2 gene, but how it performs its function was not known.
In the new study, the biologists have shown that at least part of the function of Foxp2 is to stimulate formation of new synapses in the part of the brain associated with formation of speech.
It does this with another gene, SRPX2.
The latest discoverty was made during the search for the factors that encourage the formation of synapses.
SRPX2 was one of 10 such genes, the authors found, but it was only activated via Foxp2.
What SRPX2 really affects is vocalization, scientists confirmed in experiments on mice.
When the animal's gene activation was artificially reduced, they cried less at the separation from their mother.
If the activation of the gene is restored, it restores the frequency of the sounds.
Previously the mice also showed a link between the vocalization and Foxp2.
The animals, which included a copy of the human gene pishchali activated and at a lower frequency than normal mice.
Until now, however, scientists did not know what the function of Foxp2 was and, accordingly, state-steered them with the SRPX2 purely "mechanical" properties of education sounds or thinner processes.
