Syria has destroyed their means of production of chemical weapons, the watchdog group says
Syria has destroyed the main equipment for the production of chemical weapons and toxic gas stockpiles, said the international watchdog group on Thursday, while fierce clashes raged in the north of the country, close to one of the objects which is believed to store toxic substances.
Also on Thursday, a group of Syrian activists said that more than 120 000 people were killed since the start of the civil war in the country almost three years ago.
A statement by the Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons was made one day before
The deadline of 1 November, installed given by this organisation based in the Hague to Damascus, to destroy or "make inoperable" all the means of production of chemical weapons and mechanisms that allow chemicals to mix, producing poison gas, or filling munitions with them.
The completion of what is essentially the initial phase of destruction is an important milestone in an ambitious timetable, which aims to destroy all chemical weapons of Damascus by the middle of 2014.
The destruction of the equipment means Syria can no longer make new chemical weapons.
Yet Damascus has yet to begin destroying existing weapons and supplies.
The country is believed to have about 1,000 metric tons of chemical agents and weapons, including mustard gas agents and the nerve gas sarin.
This statement was made during the fighting on Thursday in the town of al-Safira, which experts say is the facility for the production of chemical weapons, as well as the location of its store, reports British-based Syrian Center for Human Rights.
The group of activists, who watched the loss through a network of activists in Syria, said that 120 296 people had been killed.
Of this number, as it was said, 61 067 are civilians, including 6365 children.
On the part of the government, said the group, 29 954 people are members of the armed forces of President Bashar al-Assad, 18 678 are pro-government fighters and 187 - Lebanese Hezbollah militants.
Also among the dead, as stated in the statement were 2202 army defectors and about 5375 opposition fighters, many of them foreigners.
According to un estimates of 25 July, 100,000 have been killed in the conflict since March 2011.
Since then, this figure has not been updated.
The conflict forced about 2 million people to flee the country.
Assad's troops for several weeks fought in Safira with insurgents, many of whom are linked to al Qaeda groups.
The center said Thursday there were casualties on both sides, but did not give specific figures.
The fighting underscored the dangers faced by the inspectors on chemical weapons, perhaps within the tight schedule of their mission to wean syria from its toxic arsenal, in the midst of the ongoing civil war.
In a statement, the Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons, which is working in close cooperation with the United Nations, said that its team was "pleased now that it had seen and verified the removal of all Syria's declared critically important means of production and mixing / filling equipment."
It added that "no additional inspection activities are currently planned."
Earlier this week, the inspectors said they completed the first round of testing, having visited 21 of the 23 sites Damascus declared.
They have not been able to visit two places for security reasons, said the inspectors.
On Thursday, the OPCW said that both places were, according to Syria, "abandoned and... the objects of the program of chemical weapons, located in them, were relocated to other declared locations, which were checked."
It could not immediately be determined whether Safira was an object in one of two places, which OPCW inspectors have been unable to visit.
Syria presented a plan for the complete destruction of their chemical weapons, which must be approved by next month, by the executive committee of the Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons.
"I salute the courage and fortitude that you all have shown in the most complex mission ever attempted this organization," said Ahmet Uzyumdzhyu, the director general of the observer group, in comments published by the OPCW.
This is already the third year of civil war of the insurgents, mostly Sunni Muslims, with the government of Assad and his security forces, which consist of members of his Alawite sect, a branch of Shia Islam.
As for other events, head of the Centre Rami Abdurrahman said there was a strong blast on Wednesday at the site of Syria's air defenses in the coastal province of Latakia.
The cause of the explosion is unknown, he said.
