Bombardier profit declines with falling supplies and more orders for planes
Bombardier Corporation, the Canadian aircraft and train maker, reported on thursday a net profit reduction of 15 percent under the influence of a reduced quantity of orders and deliveries of aircraft in the third quarter and problems with contracts in its rail division.
Located in montreal, Bombardier also has not published any data for flight testing of its new C Series aircraft and provided no new information about whether it has implemented ambitious plans for the introduction of the aircraft into commercial operation by next September.
After the first flight of a prototype of the aircraft, held about six months ago, it flew only three times, which raises questions about whether the testing phase is on schedule.
The results have failed to meet forecasts and led to the shares falling more than 8 percent on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
On Thursday, Cameron Doerksen, an analyst at National Bank Financial, lowered its estimate of "above average" to "below average" because of the belief that share growth is limited in the next quarter or two.
"Although the reduction in the number of aircraft deliveries was largely predictable, we are, of course, disappointed by the Transport Department profit figures," said Doerksen in a review of the stock market.
We believe that bombardier is geting new C Series orders as the flight test program proceeds.
Nevertheless, if in the coming months nothing is announced about new orders, we expect that the market will become more skeptical of the program.
Bombardier hopes that the C Series family of aircraft will allow it to win a place in the lower price segment of the market, which is now dominated by Boeing and Airbus.
The first prototype of the aircraft was introduced in March, and made the first flight in September after several months of delay.
However, the company's C Series orders so far are not very many: 177, because potential buyers are waiting for the results of the flight tests to check the company's claims about fuel efficiency and potential efficiency of the new liner.
At the moment, there are 403 orders and 15 agreements with the customers and operators.
Chief Executive Officer Pierre Boduan was confident that Bombardier will reach its target of 300 firm orders by the time the first plane will be put into commercial operation.
Also on Thursday, executives assured analysts and the media that the program is progressing according to plan.
"A test model of the aircraft has not stayed on the ground longer than expected, "said Boduan during a conference call, adding that the aircraft downtime was for planned ground tests and software updates.
All manufacturers plan to test different ways.
We decided to spend the first flight and make a break for updates, and so we did.
This will also occur during the flight test programme.
The second of five test samples should take flight in the coming weeks, and all the rest will follow soon behind it, according to the company.
However, analysts are skeptical of the claim that the clients will be able to start operating C Series aircraft within the 12 months after its first flight.
Bombardier said that it will evaluates the commissioning and provide new information in the next few months.
"The slow pace of flight testing - though, apparently corresponds to Bombardier's domestic schedule, and reinforces our view that commissioning will be postponed until the first quarter of 2015, "said Doerksen.
